collation.p: VisColl collation. The collation of the last three quires is tentative. Quires and leaves were misplaced when the manuscript was rebound. On a catchword refers to . Several leaves appear to be attached singletons.
collation.catchwords: Catchwords by different hands in different places on most quires, see e.g. and .

p.note: Top left corner, National Library book label with current signum; bottom left corner in ink: 1912/45 (accession number).

binding.p: Modern binding. Leather and marbled paper over cardboard. , stamped in gold: TH. DE HASELBACH COLLATIONES DE CONFESSIONE, A 210.

origin.p: Germany , 15th century, middle of. All watermarks seem to point to southern Germany or Austria and the middle of the 15th century. The inclusion of a bull by Nicholas V (1397–1455) gives a terminus post quem for that particular text (which appears to be a later addition).

acquisition.p: Purchased by the National Library at the estate auction of Christian Hammer in Stockholm .

handDesc.p: Many different scribes have contributed to the texts, especially to the first text, Summa theologiae. Here, six different hands seem to be involved.
handDesc.handNote: Cursive or possibly semi-hybrida, some irregular looping.

p.note: Scattered additions in the margin by the scribe or a contemporary hand, and at least one additional hand. The marginal text consist of corrections, additions of omitted text keyed to the main text with signes-de-renvoi, and glossing; e.g. on , a refrence to another chapter or text. decoDesc.p: Main text in black or brown ink, capitals touched in red.

decoNote.p: : opening historiated initial P over 18 lines in gold, outlined in red and black ink with flourishing in red. The counterspace contains an image of Thomas Aquinas seated at a lectern, which has an open book on it. At the master's feet are five seated monks, three of which have covered heads and are holding open books. On the master's shoulder sits a white dove and on his head a hat. The image is painted in thick opaque colours. The main colours are: yellow for the lectern, white and black for the clothes and a blue background. The initial extends into a 3/4 border of green acanthus leaves and with red and blue flowers. : chapters are opened by plain initials over 2-6 lines in red. From there is spaced reserved for intitials, but no initials. , : texts opened by a plain initial over 3 lines in red. : paragraphs opened by plain initials over 2-4 lines in red.
